Abstract = {We present a first-principles theoretical study employing nonlinear
   response theory to investigate the dc photocurrent generated by linearly
   polarized light in the type-II Weyl semimetal TaIrTe4. We report the
   low-energy spectrum of several nonlinear optical effects. At second
   order, we consider the shift and injection currents. Assuming the
   presence of a built-in static electric field, at third order we study
   the current-induced shift and injection currents, as well as the jerk
   current. We discuss our results in the context of a recent experiment
   measuring an exceptionally large photoconductivity in this material
   {[}J. Ma et al., Nat. Mater. 18, 476 (2019)]. According to our results,
   the jerk current is the most likely origin of the large response.
   Finally, we propose means to discern the importance of the various
   mechanisms involved in a time-resolved experiment.},
